@node Introduction

    These four utilities are made to digitize anything you want to your
disk @{" (RecToDisk) " link "RecToDisk" 0} with no limitation of memory (Direct Recording
to Disk), play it back in stereo @{" (PlayFromDisk) " link "PlayFromDisk"0} and of course
crunch it or not.

    You can also crunch your old samples with @{" Crunch " link "Crunch" 0}
and decrunch 'em with @{" Decrunch " link "Decrunch" 0} .

    You can digitize the left voice first, of your favourite piece of
sound with RecToDisk, and when it's finished you can do the same with the
right voice. Then you'll have two files on your hard disk, and you'll be
able to play them back in STEREO with PlayFromDisk.

    Note that you can have a shift between the two voices, so to eliminate
it, use the shift option (see @{" PlayFromDisk " link "PlayFromDisk"0} ).

@endnode


@node RecToDisk

    This utility is used to record samples to disk. The samples may be
crunched with @{"ADPCM" link "ADPCM" 0}  2 or 3 or not. It crunches in real time.

    The samples are directly taken from the parallel port, and as I had
no documentations it is only possible to use generic digitizers. If you
have a PSound 3 or a DSS or anything else and if you know how it works,
just write to me at the above @{"address" link "Author" 0} .

    There is a monitoring on one of the speakers, but don't vorry if it is
bad quality, the record on disk is better.

    I didn't want to monitor the samples to screen because at such a
sample rate you have to kill the system and from my point of view it is
inacceptable. So to set the level of recording just use your favourite
software.

Usage :  RecToDisk <File Name> <Sample Rate> <Type of Compression>

    Sample Rate is between 0 and 28800 Hz, Type of conversion is 2, 3 or
nothing respectively ADPCM2, ADPCM3, No compression(stored in RAW).

@endnode


@node PlayFromDisk

    This utility is used to play the samples by reading them block per
block directly from the disk. This makes this utility using a very little
amount of CHIP RAM. It enables you to play one file at the left speaker
and one other at right file, so you can reproduce stereo. Therefore you
can also shift the right file in the time, if your files are not begining
at the same time. Also if your left file is "in late" regarding right
file, you'll have to invert them since you can only shift right file.


Usage : PlayFromDisk NAMEL/A,NAMER,SHIFT/K/N,FREQL/K/N,FREQR/K/N,FREQ/K/N

Where :

    NameL is the left file

    NameR is the right file

    Shift is in samples and is between 0 and 65535. At a sample rate of
28800 (which is the maximum) this is corresponding to a delay between 0
and approximatively 2 seconds.

    FreqL is the frequency for the left file if its type is RAW, so is
FreqR for right.

    Freq is for both channels and may not be used with FreqL and FreqR.

    If the file is raw and you didn't told to the program the frequency,
it will ask you.

Example : PlayFromDisk Quench_L.adpcm3 Quench_R.adpcm3 shift=2000

 PlayFromDisk Quench_L.raw Quench_R.raw shift=2000 Freq=28800

Note that you do not have to put the adpcm2 or 3 extension behind your
file, since there is a header in the file that indicates type of
compression and sample rate (see @{"ADPCM" link "ADPCM" 0} ).

As I disable Amiga's filter at 7KHz (it eats all high frequencies), a
little noise can be heard in the very high frequencies, when the level is
very low (e.g. a cappella singer). So for purists, I advise you to put
a Low-Pass filter set to 14000Hz on each channel.

While playing if you notice a little slow down while playfromdisk loads,
it's normal: to avoid gap in the sound, the process is at priority 10.

@endnode


@node Crunch

    Crunches a RAW sample to @{"ADPCM2" link "ADPCM" 0} or ADPCM3.

Usage : Crunch <source> <dest> <type> <sample rate>

    where type equals 2 or 3

    and sample rate is the frequency of your RAW file.

@endnode


@node Decrunch

    Decrunches an @{"ADPCM2" link "ADPCM" 0} or ADPCM3 sample to RAW.

    Type is automatically recognized.

Usage : Decrunch <source> <dest>

@endnode


@node ADPCM

    All utilities of this package are using the ADPCM compression, which
is very efficient: a 8Meg sample is reduced to 3Meg with ADPCM3 and to
2Meg with ADPCM2. 

    For example Robert Miles' Children which is 4 minutes long, takes
2.6Meg per channel with a sample rate of 28800 Hz and the ADPCM3
compression. If you calculate the storage price on the hard disk, you'll
see that it is almost 4 times cheaper than the CD itself.

    The 2 or 3 behind ADPCM is the number of bits used to encode the
sample.

    The dark side of the force, is that it is a destructive
compression. From the author of the ADPCM routines, the ADPCM3 is
equivalent to a good tape recording and ADPCM2 is equivalent to a poor
tape recording.

    The header of an ADPCM file is as following :

    6 Bytes: identifier: "ADPCM2" or "ADPCM3"                             
    4 Bytes: the replay frequency in Hz as ULONG
    n Bytes: cruched sample data in ADPCM format

    All the routines can be found in the ADPCM_Package written by
Christian Buchner and is availlable at Aminet util/pack/ADPCM_Package.lha

@endnode


